              "text": "{\n  \"study\": \"Luo et al. 2022\",\n  \"population\": \"Adult patients (age ≥18 years) with sepsis (defined by Sepsis-3 criteria) admitted to internal medicine or surgical ICUs.\",\n  \"sample_size\": \"N=2057 (911 non-survivors, 1146 survivors)\",\n  \"predictor\": \"Hematocrit (HCT) level (categorized as low, regular, or high based on sex-specific quartiles)\",\n  \"outcome\": \"30-day all-cause mortality\",\n  \"timing\": \"HCT measured within the first 24 hours of ICU admission; mortality assessed at 30 days.\",\n  \"method\": \"Retrospective cohort study using the MIMIC-IV database (2008–2019); univariate and multivariable Cox proportional hazards regression; Kaplan-Meier survival analysis.\",\n  \"effect_size\": \"Low HCT vs. Regular HCT: Adjusted HR = 1.589 (95% CI: 1.099–2.297, p < 0.001); High HCT vs. Regular HCT: Adjusted HR = 1.330 (95% CI: 1.007–1.757, p = 0.055).\",\n  \"performance\": \"Not reported\",\n  \"notes\": \"Low HCT was identified as an independent risk factor for 30-day mortality. HCT levels were defined by sex: Low (male ≤42%, female ≤37%), Regular (male 42%–49%, female 37%–44%), and High (male ≥49%, female ≥44%). Evidence extracted from text, Tables 1-3, and Figure 1 (Kaplan-Meier curves). A discrepancy was noted between the abstract and Table 3 regarding the confidence interval; Table 3 values were used.\",\n  \"source_info\": {\n    \"file\": \"Luo_2022.pdf\",\n    \"center_page\": null,\n    \"page_range\": {\n      \"start\": 1,\n      \"end\": 9\n    },\n    \"included_pages\": [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8, 9],\n    \"chunk\": \"all_pages_combined\"\n  }\n}",
